15:10.977 --> 15:21.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, 30 years
on from the
Chernobyl nuclear disaster, the
fallout from

15:21.554 --> 15:26.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that fateful day still haunts
Europe as a
somber anniversary is marked.

15:26.759 --> 15:29.162 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(BELL TOLLING)

15:29.262 --> 15:35.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Bells tolled
30 times in
Kiev, once for each year since
the world's

15:35.835 --> 15:38.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
worst nuclear disaster.

15:38.271 --> 15:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president of Ukraine spoke
at Chernobyl
itself.

15:40.807 --> 15:45.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETRO POROSHENKO, Ukrainian
President (through
translator): The Chernobyl
accident will for

15:45.711 --> 15:51.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a long time remain an event of a
worldwide
scale that is a challenge to the
whole of

15:51.217 --> 15:54.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
humanity. Such catastrophes do
not respect
state borders.

15:54.220 --> 15:59.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The city of
Pripyat, where
the nuclear plant was located,
is now a ghost

15:59.725 --> 16:04.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
town. It sits in the middle of
an uninhabitable
exclusion zone, where hundreds
of towns and

16:04.997 --> 16:09.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
villages in Ukraine and Belarus
were forced
to evacuate.

16:09.335 --> 16:13.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ukraine was still part of the
old Soviet Union
when Chernobyl's number four
reactor suffered

16:13.873 --> 16:22.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a catastrophic power surge on
April 26, 1986.
That triggered a meltdown and
explosion, spewing

16:22.148 --> 16:27.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
huge amounts of radioactive
material into
the atmosphere. Millions of
people across

16:27.353 --> 16:30.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Eastern Europe were exposed to
dangerously
high radiation.

16:31.023 --> 16:36.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it took two days for Soviet
authorities
to acknowledge the incident
publicly. Some

16:36.329 --> 16:42.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
600,000 troops and volunteers
were sent in
to fight the fire and clean up
contamination,

16:42.335 --> 16:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and 30 died from radiation
poisoning.

16:45.004 --> 16:49.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I went
in there
when everyone was fleeing. We
were going right

16:49.842 --> 16:53.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the heat. And, today,
everything is forgotten.
It's a disgrace.

16:53.813 --> 16:58.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The stricken
reactor was
encased in a concrete
sarcophagus. Work is

16:59.085 --> 17:04.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now under way on a steel-clad
structure to
enclose the site and prevent
further radioactive

17:04.757 --> 17:07.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leaks, at a cost of more than $2
billion.

17:08.060 --> 17:13.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The human toll is less clear,
but the World
Health Organization estimates
long-term radiation

17:13.132 --> 17:17.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
effects will claim at least
9,000 lives.

17:17.403 --> 17:22.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some further perspective on the
impact of
Chernobyl, first more on the
science, consequences,

17:22.808 --> 17:27.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fears and risks of nuclear power
from our
science correspondent, Miles
O'Brien, who's

17:27.113 --> 17:31.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
done extensive reporting in
Chernobyl and
at the more recent accident site
in Fukushima,

17:31.183 --> 17:33.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Japan.

17:33.152 --> 17:36.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles, you're one of the few
people that have
gone to both of these places.
You were reporting

17:36.155 --> 17:41.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from Chernobyl just four or five
years ago.
Put this disaster in
perspective.

17:41.694 --> 17:47.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, Hari,
Chernobyl, by any
measure, had a greater impact.

17:48.000 --> 17:53.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the radiation released
from Chernobyl
was about six times greater than
what we saw

17:53.572 --> 17:58.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
released from Fukushima. Both of
them were
so-called level seven accidents,
which is

17:58.177 --> 18:02.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the worst kind of accident on
the scale that
the international community puts
upon them.

18:02.982 --> 18:09.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Chernobyl, because it had an
explosion
and a fire, caused the spread of
radioactive

18:09.622 --> 18:14.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
material over a much broader
area. Much of
Europe was affected by it. And
so it had a

18:15.061 --> 18:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tremendous impact, not only
potentially health-wise,
but also politically and
emotionally, and

18:21.334 --> 18:23.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had a great impact on how people
viewed nuclear
power.

18:24.036 --> 18:28.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Right. I mean,
Americans
remember sort of Three Mile
Island, but Chernobyl

18:28.174 --> 18:31.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was as important in the timeline
of how the
world perceives it.

18:31.944 --> 18:33.746 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes.

18:33.846 --> 18:36.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Americans had sort of made up
their mind about
nuclear power already. We made
up our mind

18:36.315 --> 18:39.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here in the mid-'70s that we
were scared of
it, "China Syndrome" and then,
of course,

18:39.318 --> 18:41.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Three Mile Island.

18:41.187 --> 18:45.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Of course, Three Mile Island,
there was a
barely measurable amount of
radiation that

18:45.524 --> 18:49.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
escaped from the containment
vessel. In the
case of Chernobyl, there was no
containment

18:49.829 --> 18:54.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vessel whatsoever. And so there
was a big
amount of radiation which came
out.

18:54.433 --> 19:00.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it really laid the
groundwork for the
reaction that many Europeans had
toward Fukushima

19:00.306 --> 19:04.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
25 years later. You saw the
Germans, most
notably, pulling the plug on
their nuclear

19:04.944 --> 19:09.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
program. A lot of that has its
roots in the
fact they were under a cloud of
cesium-137

19:09.482 --> 19:11.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
30 years ago.

19:11.584 --> 19:15.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That
sarcophagus that you
mentioned, that was only
supposed to be there

19:15.421 --> 19:18.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
15 years. It's still there now,
and it's still
leaking.

19:19.091 --> 19:24.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It is. And seeing
it with my
own two eyes five years ago, I
was -- it was

19:24.330 --> 19:28.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pretty scary, frankly. It looked
like something
from "Mad Max."

19:28.901 --> 19:34.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was hastily built, to say
the least,
by these liquidators, true
heroes, 600,000

19:34.507 --> 19:38.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conscripts who went in there and
shoveled
for short periods of time, many
of them with

19:38.377 --> 19:44.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
devastating consequences later
in the form
of cancer. And it is still
there. It is not

19:44.283 --> 19:46.018 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
safe.

19:46.118 --> 19:48.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this new structure which
eventually will
cover will be an improvement,
for sure.

19:48.687 --> 19:52.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, where is
nuclear now,
five years after Fukushima, 30
years after

19:52.491 --> 19:54.360 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Chernobyl?

19:54.460 --> 19:57.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's interesting,
Hari. Things
have changed a little bit on
people's perceptive

19:57.830 --> 19:59.698 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of nuclear.

19:59.799 --> 20:04.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's easy to take Chernobyl out
of the mix,
for one thing. That was a bad
reactor design.

20:04.236 --> 20:08.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can all agree it was unsafe
to have any
reactor without a containment
structure. There

20:08.107 --> 20:13.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are still 11 of those types of
reactors running
in Russia now. But the West
never adopted

20:13.746 --> 20:17.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this type of graphite, moderated
reactor.

20:17.349 --> 20:22.888 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So what has happened,
interestingly, even
five years after Fukushima, is a
lot of people

20:22.988 --> 20:28.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
are coming around to the
conclusion that in
order to truly fight climate
change, the type

20:28.861 --> 20:35.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of base load power, power that
stays on all
the time, at night, that is zero
carbon emission,

20:35.968 --> 20:37.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is in fact nuclear.

20:37.903 --> 20:41.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's interest in the
business community
in this. A D.C. think tank
recently conducted

20:42.074 --> 20:48.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a study. They found 50 start-ups
in the U.S.
in the nuclear space attracting
$1.5 billion

20:48.147 --> 20:51.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in investment. So, it's kind of
an odd outcome,
actually.

20:51.183 --> 20:54.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
