government; plus, an artist's
vision to reshape

25:23.188 --> 25:26.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and revitalize Chicago's South
Side.

25:26.592 --> 25:33.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now: how life after college can
be influenced
by choices made before students
even enroll,

25:33.665 --> 25:36.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and why it can matter for their
financial
futures.

25:36.368 --> 25:40.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's part of our weekly
education segment,
Making the Grade.

25:40.172 --> 25:42.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
William Brangham has our
conversation.

25:42.941 --> 25:46.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a big week for high school
seniors across
the country. They have got to
make those final

25:46.712 --> 25:51.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decisions on where they will go
to college
next year. To celebrate,
celebrities and athletes

25:51.717 --> 25:55.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
joined first lady Michelle Obama
for a signing
day ceremony in New York City
today.

25:55.120 --> 26:01.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHELLE OBAMA, First Lady: No
matter what
path any of us on the stage took
to our success,

26:01.193 --> 26:07.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we all know that completing your
education
past high school is the most
important thing

26:07.299 --> 26:12.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you can do to reach your dreams.
That's why
we're here. So, while you all
might be in

26:12.204 --> 26:16.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
awe of us, let me tell you, we
are in awe
of you.

26:16.842 --> 26:20.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: High schoolers
and their
parents are obviously focused on
what school

26:20.379 --> 26:25.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they will go to, but a new book
argues there
are more important things to
consider.

26:25.217 --> 26:29.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The book is called "There Is
Life After College."
Jeffrey Selingo is the author. I
talked with

26:29.955 --> 26:31.657 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
him yesterday.

26:31.757 --> 26:35.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeff, if I can discern a basic
thesis from
you book, it's not so much where
you go to

26:35.794 --> 26:38.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
college, but it's what you do
while you're
in college. Is that right?

26:38.997 --> 26:40.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY SELINGO, Author, "There
Is Life After
College": That's right.

26:40.966 --> 26:44.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It used to be as long that, as
you had a bachelor's
degree from a college, any
college, really,

26:45.070 --> 26:49.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you would be golden in the job
market. It
was really the way that you got
jobs years

26:49.408 --> 26:51.310 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ago.

26:51.410 --> 26:53.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now the fact of the matter
is that there's
a lot of noise around the signal
of a bachelor's

26:53.846 --> 26:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
degree. So it's really important
what you
do while you're there, the
experiential learning

26:57.416 --> 27:03.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you get, internships,
projects, study
abroad, and activities like
that, cocurricular

27:03.989 --> 27:05.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
activities, whether it's
athletics or clubs.

27:05.924 --> 27:09.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, most importantly, you don't
take on too
much debt. The more debt that
you take on

27:09.695 --> 27:14.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in college, the fewer options
you have after
college to take essentially any
job you want

27:14.366 --> 27:17.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anywhere in the country, which
would be good
for your career, and instead
you're basing

27:17.803 --> 27:20.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
your career decisions on how
much money you're
going to make.

27:20.506 --> 27:24.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In one of the
early chapters
of your book, you categorize
graduates after

27:24.877 --> 27:26.645 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
college into three categories.

27:26.745 --> 27:31.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have the sprinters, the
wanderers, and
the stragglers. What do those
delineations

27:31.250 --> 27:33.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tell us about post-college life
today?

27:33.919 --> 27:36.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY SELINGO: Well, it used
to be that,
again, as long as you went to
college, you

27:36.822 --> 27:39.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were a sprinter. You would come
out of college
and you would have a job. You
would usually

27:39.858 --> 27:44.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
work in one occupation,
sometimes for one
employer, for most cases.

27:44.963 --> 27:48.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the fact of the matter is
that only about
a third of students now launch
from college

27:48.800 --> 27:54.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in that way. So two-thirds are
either wanderers
or the stragglers. They take
half their 20s

27:54.406 --> 27:59.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to get going in a career. In
some cases, those
are the wanderers. In other
cases, they're

27:59.311 --> 28:01.213 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stragglers, and they take most
of their 20s.

28:01.313 --> 28:06.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what are the markers of
those different
people? Well, for one thing,
sprinters intern

28:06.251 --> 28:08.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at least 80 percent of the time
in college.

28:08.487 --> 28:10.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: While they are
in college?

28:10.355 --> 28:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY SELINGO: Yes, 80 percent
have at least
one internship while in college,
as opposed

28:15.260 --> 28:19.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the wanderers. Only about 50
percent of
them intern. And the stragglers,
only about

28:19.765 --> 28:21.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
20 percent of them intern.

28:21.600 --> 28:26.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other big marker is debt.
So, sprinters
have less than $10,000 worth of
debt when

28:26.572 --> 28:31.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they come out of college. The
average today
is about $30,000. The more you
debt you have,

28:31.109 --> 28:33.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the fewer options you have after
college.

28:33.712 --> 28:37.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other big marker of the
stragglers is,
99 percent of them have some
college credit,

28:37.849 --> 28:42.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but they don't yet have a
degree. And this
is one of the bigger concerns
right now, is

28:42.220 --> 28:47.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that 70 percent of students go
right on to
college after high school, but
only about

28:47.626 --> 28:49.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
50 percent of them end up
graduating.

28:49.861 --> 28:54.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So we have a number of
millennials now with
some college credit and no
degree. And, in

28:54.399 --> 28:58.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fact, they make up the bulk of
people today
in the United States who have
some college

28:58.537 --> 29:00.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
credit and no degree to show for
their efforts.

29:01.039 --> 29:05.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You report
that a lot of
employers feel like colleges are
not doing

29:05.277 --> 29:10.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a very good job of preparing
graduates for
the work world. You quote one
employer saying

29:10.949 --> 29:13.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that these student have been
syllabused to
death. What does that mean?

29:13.952 --> 29:17.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY SELINGO: It means that
college has
a certain cadence to it, right?

29:17.222 --> 29:21.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You start in September, you end
in May, you
get a syllabus and a course
catalog at the

29:21.660 --> 29:25.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
beginning of the semester. It
kind of lays
out what you need to do. The
syllabus tells

29:25.163 --> 29:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you when things are due, when
papers are due,
when tests are due. It's
essentially a recipe

29:29.701 --> 29:31.436 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to get an A.

29:31.536 --> 29:33.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have plenty of breaks.
There's a certain
cadence to it. Then these
students get into

29:34.072 --> 29:39.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the work force, and the work
force is a mash-up
of activities. You know, it's
not task-based

29:39.611 --> 29:42.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anymore. It used to be that
jobs, you would
get a list of things to do every
day, you

29:43.081 --> 29:47.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would clock in at 9:00 and clock
out at 5:00.
No job works like that anymore,
but yet our

29:47.753 --> 29:50.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
education system is still very
task-based
in that way.

29:50.956 --> 29:55.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But you write
also that
employers as a whole often feel
that colleges

29:55.627 --> 29:58.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
should be doing a better job of
this, but
the colleges push back and say,
no, these

29:58.630 --> 30:02.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
companies are simply offshoring
and making
us job-train them, when that
should be their

30:03.068 --> 30:04.202 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
job.

30:04.302 --> 30:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Who should -- where should this
responsibility
lay?

30:06.138 --> 30:09.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY SELINGO: Well, really,
the responsibility
lies really with all three
groups.

30:09.441 --> 30:14.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really lies with colleges to
give people
both the broad skills they need
to succeed

30:14.880 --> 30:19.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not only in the workplace of
today, but tomorrow,
but also to give them some
opportunities for

30:19.351 --> 30:23.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hands-on training. And it's also
lies with
the students to go out and get
that. Many

30:23.789 --> 30:26.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students just sleepwalk through
college. They
go there and they think college
is going to

30:26.892 --> 30:28.727 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
happen to them.

30:28.827 --> 30:33.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then it's also the role of
the employers.
And many employers are not --
they are kind

30:33.565 --> 30:37.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of -- they confuse students on
this front.
In other words, you have the
CEOs of some

